  "text": "Two major classes described the overall clustering patterns of the phena (Fig. 3) . The first class contained phena 1 through 3, which were most similar to one another. The second class contained phenon [CITATION_1] (Fig. 3) . The fact that these isolates were very different from the other three phena resulted in a larger number of shared negative traits. In fact, strains included in phenon 4 joined at average S. of 67%, thereby including a total of nine strains.",
